(X) Fewer than 100 sample cases (either men or women).  Base figure too small to meet statistical standards for reliability.
-  An '-' entry in the median earnings columns indicates that no sample observations or too few sample observations were available to compute an estimate.
1 Occupation codes are based on the Standard Occupational Classification 2000.

2 Estimates are based on survey data and are subject to sampling error. Prior to the implementation of the American Community Survey, presentation of the margin of error was not standard. For information on calculating standard errors for Census 2000 estimates and information on confidentiality protection, sampling error, nonsampling error, and definitions, see http://www.census.gov/prod/cen2000/doc/sf3.pdf.

3 Estimates and median earnings may differ from a previously released Census Bureau report highlighting estimates and median earnings by sex in select occupations (Weinberg, Daniel H. 2004. "Evidence From Census 2000 About Earnings by Detailed Occupation for Men and Women." Census 2000 Special Reports CENSR-15.). The previously released report counts teachers working 37 or more weeks per year as full-time, year-round workers. Median earnings may differ due to improvements in methodology for calculating median earnings applied to this table.
4 To protect confidentiality, the number of workers is rounded to the nearest 10. Due to rounding, numbers may not add up to the totals presented.
